    quickAnswer: "Rental turnover cleaning prepares a unit for new tenants by deep cleaning all rooms, sanitizing bathrooms and kitchens, cleaning appliances, and addressing any damage or staining from previous occupants.",
    keyTakeaways: ["Schedule turnover cleaning immediately after move-out", "Professional cleaning reduces vacancy time between tenants", "Document unit condition with photos before and after", "Address carpet stains and wall marks during turnover", "Regular turnover cleaning protects property value long-term"],
    content: "## Rental Property Turnover Cleaning: A Landlord's Guide\n\nA property manager in Shingle Springs called me on a Friday afternoon. A tenant had moved out that morning. The new tenant was moving in Monday. He needed the 3-bedroom unit cleaned over the weekend.\n\nWhen we walked in, the place was rough. Grease caked in the kitchen, pink mold in the shower, mystery stains on the carpet. The previous tenant clearly did not do a move-out clean.\n\nWe had it rent-ready by Sunday morning. The new tenant moved in Monday with zero complaints. That is how turnover cleaning should work when you have the right team on call.\n\n---\n\n## Why Turnover Cleaning Matters\n\nEvery day a unit sits empty is money lost. In El Dorado County, the average rent for a 2-bedroom is around $1,800 per month. That is $60 per day of vacancy.\n\nA professional turnover clean that gets your unit rent-ready in 24 to 48 hours pays for itself immediately compared to a week of vacancy while you scramble to clean it yourself or wait for an available service.\n\n### What Tenants Notice First\n\nNew tenants form their impression of the property in the first 5 minutes. These are the areas that set the tone:\n\n- **Kitchen appliances.** A dirty oven or stained stovetop tells them the property is not well maintained.\n- **Bathroom grout.** Discolored grout says \"old.\" Clean grout says \"cared for.\"\n- **Floors.** Scuff marks, dust lines along walls, and dirty carpet give the impression nobody inspected the unit.\n- **Smell.** Stale air, pet odor, or leftover cooking smells from the previous tenant are immediate turnoffs.\n\n---\n\n## The Turnover Cleaning Checklist\n\n### Kitchen\n\n- Oven interior and racks deep cleaned\n- Stovetop and burner pans degreased\n- Refrigerator cleaned inside and out (remove shelves and drawers)\n- Microwave and dishwasher interiors wiped\n- Countertops and backsplash scrubbed\n- Sink and faucet polished\n- Cabinet interiors and fronts wiped\n- Floor mopped including under appliances\n\n### Bathrooms\n\n- Toilet disinfected (bowl, seat, base, behind)\n- Shower or tub scrubbed including grout\n- Glass doors or curtain hardware cleaned\n- Vanity, sink, and mirror polished\n- Cabinet interiors wiped\n- Exhaust fan dusted\n- Floor mopped\n\n### All Rooms\n\n- Floors vacuumed and mopped\n- Baseboards wiped\n- Light fixtures dusted\n- Ceiling fans cleaned\n- Window sills and tracks cleared\n- Blinds dusted or wiped\n- Closets wiped out\n- Doors and frames spot-cleaned\n- All hardware sanitized (switches, handles, knobs)\n\n---\n\n## Setting Up a Turnover System\n\nIf you manage multiple properties, ad hoc cleaning is not sustainable. Here is how to build a reliable turnover process.\n\n### Have a Cleaning Service on Retainer\n\nYou do not need a contract. You need a relationship with a cleaning company that can respond quickly when a tenant moves out. At Alexa's Cleaning, several of our property management clients have us on a preferred vendor list. When a unit opens up, they call and we schedule within 48 hours.\n\n### Create a Standard Inspection Checklist\n\nUse the same checklist for every move-out inspection and every turnover clean. This keeps expectations consistent for tenants, cleaners, and new occupants. The [California Apartment Association](https://caanet.org/) offers resources for landlords managing rental properties in the state.\n\n### Document Everything\n\nBefore and after photos protect both you and your tenants. We can provide documentation of unit condition after our cleaning, which supports fair deposit assessments.\n\n---\n\n## Pricing for Landlords and Property Managers\n\n| Unit Size | Turnover Clean |\n|---|---|\n| Studio / 1 bed | $150 to $220 |\n| 2 bed / 1 bath | $200 to $300 |\n| 3 bed / 2 bath | $280 to $400 |\n| 4+ bed | $350 to $500+ |\n\nCondition matters. A unit from a clean tenant who did a move-out scrub costs less than a unit left in rough shape. We provide honest quotes after a quick walkthrough or photo assessment.\n\n---\n\n## Alexa's Take: Treat It Like a Business\n\nI work with landlords who treat their rentals like investments and landlords who treat them like headaches. The difference usually comes down to systems.\n\nA consistent turnover process with a reliable cleaning team means less vacancy, fewer tenant complaints, and better reviews on rental platforms. It is one of the simplest upgrades you can make to your property management workflow.\n\n---\n\n## Get Your Unit Rent-Ready\n\n[Get a free estimate](https://www.alexascleaningplacerville.com) or call **(530) 214-6361**. Fast turnaround, consistent quality, no contracts.",
